<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">27167713</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2018</Year><Month>01</Month><Day>08</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2018</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>02</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1827-1928</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>57</Volume><Issue>11</Issue><PubDate><Year>2017</Year><Month>Nov</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>The Journal of sports medicine and physical fitness</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Sports Med Phys Fitness</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Increasing training load without risking the female athlete triad: menstrual cycle based periodized training may be an answer?</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1519</StartPage><EndPage>1525</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1519-1525</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.23736/S0022-4707.16.06444-6</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">An improved muscle strength are of great importance in many sports, hence an increased understanding on how to generate optimal strength training programs in women without negative side effects that may lead to the female athlete triad are essential. The purpose of this study was to investigate potential negative effects of high frequency periodized menstrual/oral contraceptives (OC) cycle based leg resistance training on components in the female athlete triad.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Fifty-nine women, with experience of resistance training and with regular menstrual/OC cycles were included in the analyses. The participants were randomly assigned a training program consisted of high frequency leg resistance training, periodized to the first two weeks (group 1) or the last two weeks (group 2) of each cycle, or to a control group performing regular training, during four consecutive menstrual/OC cycles. The main analysis was the pre-to-post change of sex and growth hormones, cortisol, total body fat mass, bone mineral density in the spine. We further examined the participants' own experience of the training programs.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">No significant negative impact on sex and growth hormones, cortisol, total body fat mass and bone mineral density in the spine, was detected in any of the groups. Moreover, the women in group 1 experienced their training program as positive.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">The high frequency periodized leg resistance training was not associated with exercise-related negative consequences on components in the female athlete triad. Moreover, the training was well accepted when performed during the first two weeks of each cycle.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wikstr&#xf6;m-Fris&#xe9;n</LastName><ForeName>Lisbeth</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Unit of Sports Medicine, Department of Community Medicine and Rehabilitation, Ume&#xe5; University, Ume&#xe5;, Sweden - lisbeth.wikstrom-frisen@umu.se.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Boraxbekk</LastName><ForeName>Carl-Johan</ForeName><Initials>CJ</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Center for Demographic and Aging Research (CEDAR), Ume&#xe5; University, Ume&#xe5;, Sweden.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Henriksson-Lars&#xe9;n</LastName><ForeName>Karin</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Unit of Sports Medicine, Department of Community Medicine and Rehabilitation, Ume&#xe5; University, Ume&#xe5;, Sweden.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>The Swedish School of Sport and Health Sciences, Stockholm, Sweden.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><Publicati